1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,850
We human beings are curious creatures.

2
00:00:02,960 --> 00:00:06,049
We're quick to accept full credit for our victories.

3
00:00:06,160 --> 00:00:09,250
When we win, we want the world to know about it.

4
00:00:09,440 --> 00:00:15,490
It's natural to want others to look at you and say, there goes the fellow who did such and such.

5
00:00:16,320 --> 00:00:21,330
But human beings are equally quick to blame someone else for each setback.

6
00:00:21,520 --> 00:00:26,210
It's natural for salesmen to blame customers when sales are lost.

7
00:00:26,400 --> 00:00:32,930
It's natural for executives to blame employees or other executives when things get out of gear.

8
00:00:33,360 --> 00:00:40,210
It's natural for husbands to blame wives and wives to blame husbands for quarrels and family problems.

9
00:00:40,880 --> 00:00:45,409
It is true that in this complex world, others may trip us.

10
00:00:45,600 --> 00:00:49,970
But it is also true that more often than not, we trip ourselves.

11
00:00:50,240 --> 00:00:55,010
We lose because of personal inadequacy, some personal mistake.

12
00:00:56,400 --> 00:00:59,250
Condition yourself for success this way.

13
00:00:59,440 --> 00:01:04,529
Remind yourself that you want to be as nearly perfect as is humanly possible.

14
00:01:04,720 --> 00:01:05,889
Be objective.

15
00:01:06,080 --> 00:01:12,690
Put yourself in a glass tube and look at yourself as a disinterested third party would look at the situation.

16
00:01:13,200 --> 00:01:16,690
See if you have a weakness that you've never noticed before.

17
00:01:16,880 --> 00:01:19,650
If you have, take action to correct it.

18
00:01:20,080 --> 00:01:25,890
Many people become so accustomed to themselves that they fail to see ways for improvement.

19
00:01:26,880 --> 00:01:34,210
The great Metropolitan Opera star Reza Stevens said in Reader's Digest, July 1955,

20
00:01:34,400 --> 00:01:40,210
that at the unhappiest moment of her life, she received the best advice she's ever had.

21
00:01:40,640 --> 00:01:46,849
Early in her career, Ms. Stevens lost the Metropolitan Opera auditions of the air.

22
00:01:47,200 --> 00:01:49,970
After losing, Miss Stevens was bitter.

23
00:01:50,320 --> 00:01:55,490
I longed to hear, she said, that my voice was really better than the other girls,

24
00:01:55,600 --> 00:02:01,250
that the verdict was grossly unfair, that I had just lacked the right connections to win.

25
00:02:01,840 --> 00:02:04,849
But Miss Stevens's teacher didn't coddle her.

26
00:02:04,960 --> 00:02:11,010
Instead, she said to Miss Stevens, My dear, have the courage to face your faults.

27
00:02:11,840 --> 00:02:16,450
Much as I wanted to fall back on self-pity, continued Miss Stevens,

28
00:02:16,559 --> 00:02:19,569
they, those words, kept coming back to me.

29
00:02:19,920 --> 00:02:21,650
That night they woke me.

30
00:02:21,760 --> 00:02:24,849
I couldn't sleep until I faced my shortcomings.

31
00:02:24,960 --> 00:02:29,089
Lying there in the dark, I asked myself, why did I fail?

32
00:02:29,279 --> 00:02:31,170
How can I win next time?

33
00:02:31,440 --> 00:02:36,210
And I admitted to myself that my voice range was not as good as it had to be,

34
00:02:36,320 --> 00:02:40,930
that I had to perfect my languages, that I must learn more roles.

35
00:02:41,600 --> 00:02:47,809
Miss Stevens went on to say how facing her faults not only helped her to succeed on stage,

36
00:02:47,840 --> 00:02:52,849
but also helped her win more friends and develop a more pleasing personality.

37
00:02:53,519 --> 00:02:55,970
Being self-critical is constructive.

38
00:02:56,160 --> 00:03:01,010
It helps you to build the personal strength and efficiency needed for success.

39
00:03:01,360 --> 00:03:03,650
Blaming others is destructive.

40
00:03:03,840 --> 00:03:08,690
You gain absolutely nothing from proving that someone else is wrong.

41
00:03:09,680 --> 00:03:11,890
Be constructively self-critical.

42
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:14,370
Don't run away from inadequacies.

43
00:03:14,480 --> 00:03:16,450
Be like the real professionals.

44
00:03:16,560 --> 00:03:20,130
They seek out their faults and weaknesses, then correct them.

45
00:03:20,240 --> 00:03:22,529
That's what makes them professionals.

46
00:03:23,360 --> 00:03:27,890
Don't, of course, try to find your faults so you can say to yourself,

47
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:30,289
here's another reason I'm a loser.

48
00:03:30,720 --> 00:03:36,370
Instead, view your mistakes as, here's another way to make me a bigger winner.

49
00:03:37,519 --> 00:03:46,289
The great Orville Hubbard once said, A failure is a man who has blundered but is not able to cash in on the experience.
